What is the difference between git add and git commit?
git add requires arguments (file names or folders). it will add those arguments to the staging area.
git commit will commit (like a snapshot in the git history) those files added in the staging area.

Every commit in git stores 4 types of objects in .git/objects/ - blob, tree, commit, tag.

What is a Git hash and what is it based on?
git has is a cryptographic hashed version of the combination of the content, file type & size and running it through SHA-256
*it's SHA-1 not SHA-256. Git uses SHA-1 (moving to SHA-256 in newer versions but SHA-1 is still default). Based on content + metadata (author, timestamp, parent commit hash) — not just content.

If you commit the same file content twice, does Git store it twice?
no. it will compared against the last commit and if it is exactly the same, it will return "nothing to commit".
more like it will compare the has of the file. if the hash is same, it will do nothing.
* Git stores content-addressable objects. If the blob hash is identical, Git reuses the same blob object — it literally doesn't create a new file in .git/objects. This is called content-addressable storage. Two different files with identical content share one blob.

What is HEAD in Git?
it is the pointer to the current branch and latest commit usually unless changed with git checkout. like if we commit, it will make the changes on top of the HEAD and moves the head to the latest commit.

What is a branch in Git — is it a copy of the code?
i guess its a replica of a code under a different tree in git. we can use it for different purposes for dev, prod, testing, etc... 
A branch is just a pointer — a file containing a 40-character commit hash. That's it. No code is copied. When you create a branch, Git creates a 41-byte file in .git/refs/heads/. The entire codebase is not duplicated. This is why Git branches are so cheap compared to SVN.

What does detached HEAD mean?
it means the HEAD is in an older commit and further changes will be done on top of that. but it wouldn't affect the latest commit.
*it directly points to a commit instead of branch. new commits made here does not belong to any branch unless one is made. 

Why does Git have a staging area at all? What problem does it solve?
there is always a possibility of having unnecessary files in a project after cloning. like if we open it in an IDE, there will be some IDE specific config files. that is not required to be on git. staging resolves this problem. it will consider the files to be related to git only when the changed file is specified with git add so that even if there are many other files, it will be untracked and only the files added via git add goes to the staging area which is eligible to commit.
*Staging lets you craft commits precisely. You can make 5 changes to 5 files but only commit 3 of them in one logical commit, then commit the other 2 separately. This keeps commit history clean and meaningful.

What does git reset HEAD <file> do?
it will remove the aforementioned file from the staging area and it will be back to untracked status.
*in newer Git versions this is git restore --staged <file>. Same effect. Also git reset HEAD <file> doesn't delete changes — it just unstages them. Changes remain in working directory.

What does git stash actually do internally?
it is like a saved version of unsaved files that can be saved later if required. using stash wont affect commit history. it is for work in progress files usecase. we can just clear the stash entirely if not required. or just apply it to save them in working dir and use git add for moving to staging area.

When would you use stash vs creating a branch?
creating branch is for actual files and not working ones. it doesn't solve the problem of recording the movements in the history and it will create chaos. branch will still point to a commit whereas stash is just a bunch of saved changed without any history. branch will also affect existing files.
*Use stash when you need to quickly context-switch and come back to the same work later — temporary parking spot. Use branch when the work is significant enough to have its own history and might be reviewed or merged by others.

What is the difference between merge and rebase?
merge will merge the commits of the target branch with existing one along with the history too... leaving many under conflicts if any. now both history of commits and latest commit will be merged.
rebase just overlaps all the commits of the target branch over the current's latest commit resulting is no conflicts but a lot of commit history
*"rebase results in no conflicts" is wrong. Rebase can still have conflicts — you resolve them per commit as they're replayed. The difference is history shape, not conflict frequency. Fix: "Merge preserves full history with a merge commit showing where branches joined. Rebase replays commits linearly — cleaner history but rewrites commit hashes."

When would you use each in a team?
in a team if we're working on different tasks, we use merge. if another team wants to takeover the existing one, the can do rebase.
*too vague. Better: "Rebase for local feature branches before raising a PR — clean up your own commits. Merge for integrating completed features into main — preserves the record of what happened. Never rebase shared/public branches — it rewrites history others depend on."

What is fast-forward merge?
if there are 2 branches where 1 got diverged from another and if we proceed to make changes in the diverged branch... after some commits, we want it to be merged with the source branch and if there was no commits done in the source till now, it will make fast-forward where all those commits will be added to the source branch and pointed moved to the latest of source branch. if we strictly want the history along with it (the merge history and the branch history), we can use --no-ff flag to avoid fast-forwarding.

When would you use cherry-pick in a real project?
when i want to get a particular commit and not other history or future related to that. let's say there are multiple versions of an app and a particular version is the most stable one, and we want to get that we can use cherry-pick.

What's the risk of cherry-picking frequently?
the risk of cherry-pick when used frequently is that we may lose track of history and a lot of confusion may arrive in the main branch between versions.

What do the markers mean?
markers is used to represent the versions of the conflict. like the branch name and the separation between conflicts. we can remove it and save to resolve the conflicts.

What is git merge --abort and when would you use it?
when we are unsure of which version of the conflict to keep, we can abort the merge and can do it later.

Difference between soft, mixed, hard reset?
soft: uncommits and bring back the changes to the staging area.
mixed: uncommits but doesn't bring back to staging area. we need to add again
hard: uncommits and also deletes from local

Difference between reset and revert?
reset: deletes the last commit.
revert: creates new commit without the last commit.

Why is hard reset dangerous on shared branches?
it will delete the files permanently and is unrecoverable.

Which workflow suits a 5-person startup vs a 100-person enterprise?
for a 5 person startup, main and feature workflows are good enough.
for a 100 person enterprise startup, since there will be many features, many versions of features and etc main, feature, hotfix, release, develop workflow may be required. like each branch for each release or feature...

What is a Pull Request and what problem does it solve?
when someone made any changes in the repo and we have to get updated to the latest push, we use git pull. it will get the latest versions of all files of the repo. it may cause issue when we have a working version of a file that's been updated in the pull. we can resolve the conflict like we discussed earlier.

What does squash do in interactive rebase?
we can selectively pick commits and squash rest leading to rewriting commit history with our approval.
its like a combined meaningful commit with no extra commits. 

What is the difference between squash and fixup?
in squash we can have commit messages of all combined commits or we can edit it to our liking. but we should do it manually. 
with fixup, it is automated to have commit message of the last commit and no need to edit.

When would you use interactive rebase in a team workflow?
when we're editing the commit history and want some and don't want some specifically. without interactive, it will just move the pointer and include everything. we could give HEAD~4 for last 4 or whatever... but still we can't pick specific commits without interactive. 

What is git reflog and how is it different from git log?
reflog keeps everything recorded even the deleted branches, reset commits etc... wheread git log only has the active commits and the intended history.

How long does reflog keep entries?
90 days for reachable commits, 30days for unreachable ones where rebase, reset are used. 

When would reflog save you in a real situation?
when i accidentally delete a branch, hard reset something reflogs helps but only within the date range of the reflog.

What algorithm does git bisect use?
it uses binary search for making it insanely efficient.

Why is bisect faster than checking commits one by one?
because it uses binary search. for 100 commits, it will first check 50th commit, then 25th, then 12th, then 6th, then 3rd, then 2nd. total just 7 commits in the worst case. 

What is git fetch vs git pull?
fetch will download all objects from the origin main and save it in .git/ folder. we can use git diff origin/main to inspect the differences and latest files.

What is git remote -v and what does it show?
it will give the address (in and out) of the pull, fetch and push

What does git stash pop vs git stash apply do differently?
git stash pop will delete last stash, git stash apply will get the changes to the local and we can add it to staging area for commit.

What is a .gitignore file and how does it work?
it will get a list of file extensions (like .jpg, dockerfile, etc...) and ignore those type of files from getting recognized by git for any manipulation or commit.

What does git clean -fd do?
it will remove all untracked files from local